Understand

RISK MANAGEMENT STRATEGIES
Avoidance: don’t take the risk at all
Mitigation: Reduce the risk
Transfer: insurance, outsourcing
Acceptance: Live with it if low impact


THREAT INTELLIGENCE
Information that helps predict, prevent and respond to cyber attacks.
Why it matters is that it helps us stay ahead of attackers.

TYPES
Strategic TI, Tactical, Operational

Strategic TI
Strategic Threat Intelligence: (the tutor used the kidnapping in Okene road as example).
Big picture and long-term view (something that has been happening for long).
Audience: Executives, decision-makers.
Example: Rise of ransomware in healthcare, ransomware presents an attack that passes word all your files and you have to pay attackers to get access.

TACTICAL TI
specific attacker techniques, tactics and procedures (TTPs)
tells you specific information about the attackers, how they will operate and the procedures, gives you more information about all attackers than strategic TI.
Audience: SOC analysts, defenders.

OPERATIONAL TI
details on campaigns, malware or groups in real time.
e.g using okene road it gives you a real time of how those kidnappers are aggressive eg during festive period.
virustotal.com — use to verify a link if it is legit or scam.

SOURCES OF THREAT INTELLIGENCE
Open source intelligence (OSINT): using google to check links
Threat feeds (commercial or free): like facebook feeds
Dark web monitoring
Sharing communities

WHY WE USE THREAT INTELLIGENCE
Helps in proactive defense
Helps to respond to incident faster (incident response, faster detection & recovery)
Improving risk management

